Incident Response > [T2]: Effective Incident Communication Planning in IR

IR Communications

Rapid and effective communication is an integral part of a strong response. An incident communication plan helps you streamline the communication process by defining internal and external stakeholders who should be informed, what information should be shared, when, and the methods of communication.

NIST Computer Security Incident Handling Guide

You may wonder why I need to share incident information with external parties. In some situations, you will have to involve Internet Service Providers, vendors, or law enforcement to contain an incident. You may also have to work with IR teams from other organizations. A couple of incidents we handled involved compromised servers belonging to other organizations. The attacker compromised another organization's web server to host a phishing webpage and a couple of exploit kits. We had to notify the other organization's IR team so they could kick off an investigation, clean up the server and take down the phishing site.

Another critical aspect of the communications plan is how the IR team will communicate during the incident. Under normal circumstances, the security team will use the same communications channel the rest of the organization uses. However, when you are under fire, you should have a wholly isolated communication channel. Otherwise, attackers may be able to watch over the security team's communications and be a couple of steps ahead of you. In a previous incident, attackers were able to compromise the organization's Slack server and spy on security team communications. That's one of the worst situations a security team could experience! Side note, do you know that Canary has a Slack token/honeypot to alert the security team upon slack compromise?

Therefore, the IR team should establish out-of-band communication channels such as cellular phones, voice mailboxes, and faxes. Some teams roll out their in-house IM applications, such as RocketChat. In addition, the past years witnessed the introduction of secure chat applications such as Signal.

A typical checklist for an IR communication plan includes the following:

  • IR team phone numbers.
  • Notification list (e.g., CISO, system owner, HR, legal, IT and network teams, law enforcement, etc.).
  • Out-of-Band OOB communication channels.
  • Incident reporting channel (how end users will report incidents? submitting a form, calling a phone number, or sending an email to a particular inbox).
Finally, we have seen some organizations adopt a silence policy during incidents, thinking that by keeping it secret, things will go unnoticed. They mistakenly believe that this may avoid them the blame. Do not ever do that! Effective communication is built on transparency, and the greatest mistake a security team can make is to be afraid of making one. Without room for errors, there is no room for improvement.
